commentBody:
@B

As one who is trying to understand the artistic nature of puzzle creation, what in particular do you find substandard about this one.

I'm not disagreeing--simply looking for more information.

@Francis

Personal judgment call, as with everything, but it was just so screamingly easy, particularly with the anagram / Spelling Bee theme clues.  It felt like an old paint by numbers sheet where everything was already filled in, or the later ones where you slathered water onto a sheet and the drawing magically appeared...  It was the easiest puzzle I've ever seen published here, and it seems beneath all of us.

If I'm wrong, so be it, but that's how it struck me....

@George

I'll know you'll not respond.

But I'm still waiting to hear what people mean by "lazy" in the context of crossword construction.

@B

I wonder if all the flack constructors take here is causing fewer submissions?

I know it would depress the hell out of me.

@Mike

None other spring to mind.  You win; terrible puzzle though.

(Aww, tummy ache?)

@Mike

'Tis the season to be punny, eh?
(Just *look* at what you've started!)

@Mean Old Lady
He jolly well did.

But I'll be the first to name the 4th one, and winter race.

@Marshall Walthew
@Marshall Walthew
According to the Constructor Notes, Will Shortz calls it a "letter bank".

@SBK
I enjoyed your response to my comment yesterday so, of course, I felt the need to add to your thread with @Francis today! Last night's nail biter of a game was just EPIC in terms of the rivalry, especially when it came down to the bottom of the 9th inning - truly one of their best match-ups in years with just phenomenal pitching. Having the Red Sox pull this first game off was great and I hope they do it again tonight so they can head north to Toronto!‚öæÔ∏è

Those of us among Red Sox Nation always discover new reasons for our enduring grudge (understatement) against the Yankees, but the latest one is having the purchase of online playoff tickets for this short series in NY restricted to NY, CT, PA and NJ. Beyond unfair to the Fenway Faithful so GO RED SOX!!‚öæÔ∏è

@Laura
Rooting for the Sox tomorrow. After that  I don't care. Just so long as the WC series goes the full length. No rest for the weary!

Go, Jays!

@Laura
Agree. This was on the easier side for me (and a Wednesday PB), but I suspect it's because I picked up on the theme immediately and was able to fill in the theme answers without crossings.

But that didn't make it any less enjoyable.  I am confused by the folks that come here to complain.

@Red Carpet

When I first moved to the Twin Cities, I was just over the moon about being "half-way" from the equator to the north pole.

I've always been a lover of northern climates.

@john ezra

Holy cow, that was impressive.

Did you just think of all of those?  Or did you have them all lines up and waiting.

@Megan

The AMSTEL/ASAHI cross definitely would have gotten me had I not have Amstel flash in front of my eyes.

So, yeah, I thought that was a very naticky kind of thing:  two clues, both are foreign names, both of the same product...phew!

@Times Rita
Inquiring minds would like to know what you drank in those bars. Never beer? I guess other stuff is available. 
  Happy bar news: Brannelly's pub,at the bottom of our street, reopened last week after at least a 6-year hiatus. Son took over;he'd paid fee for the liquor license all that time. Good beer and food so far. Watched Patriots win.

@Andrzej

I don't remember seeing Anacin for a long, long time, but I grew up in the early days of television, and most commercials were fairly simple--often simple animation with the letters of the name of the product.

I don't particularly remember Anacin commercials, but the headache medication money was brutally fought over.

@Andrzej

What a fluffy face!

It's always a great moment when they ask to go out.

@Andrzej 

I first encountered an oral vaccine at about age five, when everyone in my school got lined up to receive the new polio vaccination.

I was bracing myself for a needle in the shoulder. Instead, I was handed a sugar cube with a little red stain on one side. It made me happy enough that I still remember that moment.

@Bruce

Yeah, me, too.  Almost exactly the same memory.  Was the sugar cube in one of those tiny little cups like a miniature cupcake?

I think that's the only oral one I ever had.

@Vito
I found this one difficult! Brand names, sports and TV clues,  Toledo is in Spain, kung fu, Splinter? don't know what ONLY FANS is ...... 
Nice quote from TS Eliot.

@Bruce
I immediately thought of the British documents that have seals, etc., plus I had SLY FOX there (DOGs not being particularly clever, IMHO) so between that and the Ninja Turtle thing, not to mention  the correctly-spelt "Whoa!" instead of that annoying "Woah!" for OMG....well, it was the only slightly-difficult part of the puzzle....  
Eagerly awaiting Thursday.  Don't let me down, Will!!!

@Call Me Al
You are the second to reference Sha-na-na so far, at 117 Comments (reading from Newest)....and I don't get it.
Hope that distorts the stats.

@Barry Ancona
I found Tuesday's puzzle hard, I even needed three cheats, which is rare on a Tuesday.  And I loved this Wednesday puzzle.  I admit I love the letter play.  I solve the Spelling Bee every day, never stopping until I get my crown.

Different strokes for different folks!

@Sonja and @Andrzej

The Solon city schools in NE Ohio were very slow to close for any weather-related issues.  It had to be a blizzard with high winds (think "horizontal snow/sleet") and at least below Zero....  I can count on one hand how many "snow days" were called in the 14 years we had a kid in school there...and have fingers left over.  
(I had never heard of "snow pants" until we moved to that part of Ohio.)

@James
I for one enjoyed having a Wednesday that didn't require cheating.  And I thought the theme was fun.  

(Perhaps you would like a week of all Friday and Saturday puzzles?  They sell those by the book.  (I always buy the 'Tuesday' and 'Wednesday' books.))

@Charles
Get used to Asahi and Amstel. They are crossword staples. I've run into them a few times in the last year, and so they were gimmes.

In fact, because of the crossword, the last time I was at a Japanese restaurant, I ordered Asahi and quite enjoyed it.

@MExpat

MEXpat performed a TAPA EXAM at the local bar and found MANY A GERM in GERMANY

Still love it?

@HeathieJ

I can't eat olives, either.  I had an actor friend who felt the same way, and in one show he did he had to snack on olives for an entire scene.

That's acting.

@Francis 

Oh my gosh, that sounds like the worst thing ever. What a pro!! 

I'm really not all that picky, but olives and coffee, no can do in any which way!!
